WHO   — CRIME + PUNISHMENT IN SUBURBIA — a UD0 film-world — the screen companion to CRP
WHAT  — Crime + Punishment in Suburbia — the screen companion to the novel: faithful in feeling, unfaithful in idea, with the Raskolnikov nod sewn into the heroine's surname, Skolnik.
WHERE — an American suburb — the mall, the cul-de-sac, the high school — a loose modern transposition of Dostoevsky  Framework inputs: the film (2000, dir. Rob Schmidt; writer Larry Gross); Dostoevsky's Crime and Punishment; Sundance 2000  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0 · Universe David 0)
WHY   — Because the film keeps Dostoevsky's emotional skeleton — crime, guilt, and redemption through being loved and witnessed — while trading his philosophical engine for a teenager's desperate revenge.
HOW   — Crystallized from the 2000 film: an abused teenager, Roseanne Skolnik, and her boyfriend murder her stepfather, and a watchful outsider who loves her, Vincent, becomes her witness and her way back.

awareness — what the node knows of itself:
  It kept Dostoevsky's heart and dropped his head — the crime, the guilt, and the redeeming witness survive; the philosophy does not, and it's named Skolnik so you'd know.

